post_text:
Cedar Mountain has been notified by MDE that we will be allowed to run a Summer Food Service Program (SFSP) through December 31st, 2020 or until the funds are exhausted. This program offers a free lunch and breakfast for all kids. Cedar Mountain students will be receiving their free meal during the school day.

Cedar Mountain Schools will have two daily pick up sites for those interested in getting a meal. Meals are free for anyone 18 and under.
Morgan 11:35 - 11:45 am
Franklin 12:00 - 12:15 pm

If you plan to pick up meals, we ask that you fill out the following form. This form is necessary for our food service staff to know how many meals to prepare.
Click Here to Sign Up; https://forms.gle/eFS74n3fzM3Y8yty7

It is important to note that Free and Reduced applications still need to be completed and turned in to the district office. This process is very important to our district. Please complete these as soon as possible.

Feel free to contact Lori Hacker in the district office with any questions you may have. (507) 249-5990.

Cedar Mountain is proud to announce the opening of the Fall School Age After School Child Care program, Camp Cougar!

What: Students will receive homework help as needed and enjoy a wide variety of activities and events that will enrich their education and be a lot of FUN!

post_text:
Summer Meals Update

Here is an update regarding meals and the summer meal program:

The last school year meal in Morgan and Franklin will be May 28th. Thank you to everyone who participated.

The summer meals program will begin on June 8th in Franklin only. The Franklin site is eligible for the summer program, whereas the Morgan site is not. Everyone 18 and under may still pick up a meal, regardless of where they live.

Meals in Franklin will be “Grab and Go” with breakfast and lunch being handed out at the same time. Meals will be available from 11:00 am-12:00 pm, Monday through Friday.
Those waiting for a meal must practice social distancing.

Transportation will not be provided from Morgan to Franklin for meals due to current health guidance.

Please contact the district office with any questions you may have. (507) 249-5990

Rob Brandl
Superintendent
Cedar Mountain Schools

post_text:
Graduation Update

Cedar Mountain Schools will be hosting a parking lot graduation ceremony for the Class of 2020 and their immediate families (household) only on May 29th, 2020 at 7:00 pm.

This ceremony will be broadcast live on the radio on SAM 107.3 for all to listen to. Following the ceremony, the vehicles will be led on a processional through Morgan and Franklin.

We look forward to celebrating this great group of students for all they overcame during this unprecedented time period.

Note: Cedar Mountain developed this graduation plan in accordance with MDE guidance and the guidance of county health officials. This event is not open to the general public and all participants (graduates and households) are required to stay in their vehicles the entire time.

Update/Clarification Regarding Meals

The free meal program that is being offered to anyone 18 and under will be starting on March 18th. The meals are available to anyone who lives in a community regardless of what school they attend. Non-Cedar Mountain students who live in our communities are more than welcome to stop by school and receive a free meal. Cedar Mountain students who live in surrounding communities can pick up lunches from the school located in the community where they live.

Here is a list of some meals location sites for meal pick up:

Pick Up at Cedar Mountain High School (MORGAN): 11:00-12:00 M-F Door #9 (the side door by the cafeteria)

Pick Up at the Elementary School (FRANKLIN): 11:00-12:00 M-F Door #10 (the kitchen door on the west side of school)

Morton City Hall in Morton- 11:00-11:30am M-F (Meal provided by Redwood Valley Schools)

Lower Sioux Government Center Parking Lot- 11:00-11:30am M-F (Meal provided by Redwood Valley Schools)

post_text:
No School starting Monday, March 16.

Cedar Mountain Families,

We were notified by Minnesota Governor Tim Walz that all schools in Minnesota need to be closed Wednesday, March 18th through March 27th due to the coronavirus. Schools have the option to close this week Monday and Tuesday. Cedar Mountain Schools will be closed starting Monday, March 16th through the 27th. This time will be utilized by staff to prepared for distance learning in the event of a long term school closure. The school buildings will be open on Monday and Tuesday for any students that need to pick up materials. As all of our district plans come together, we will be notifying families through Infinite Campus email and posting information on the school’s website. Feel free to contact the school offices with questions you may have.

Rob Brandl
Superintendent
Cedar Mountain Schools

post_text: On Tuesday, February 4th, Rachel Schumacher participated in a Regional Spelling Bee at the Redwood Falls Community Center. She was one of thirty-two participants. There was a written round with 25 words followed by an oral round where participants had to spell 3 words each. Based on the total from the first two rounds, 15 finalists were chosen. Rachel was the first finalist announced. She made it through two rounds before going out on the word "palindrome." Way to go Rachel!

He spoke on the history of Veterans Day, how it started as Armistice Day, and how we need to remember and think of our Veterans 365 days of the year not just one for the sacrifice they gave. The band and choir performed and the Blue Crue put together the program. The Morgan VFW were the color guard. Thanks to all for making this program possible!

Cedar Mountain Elementary PreK - Grade 5
October 30, 2019 at 5:54 PM ·

Are you interested in learning how to edit your own photographs? Are you also interested in photo manipulation and effects? Check out digital photography with Mrs. Paula Gareis. In this course, you will be able to learn photo editing and manipulation using your very own photographs. Mrs. Gareis will show you how to get the most from your photographs and even how fix some images you may need touched up. Bring a flash drive or disc containing the photographs you'd like to edit (or your phone with a USB cord). Among the skills taught will be: fixing exposure, sharpening and softening images, double exposures, removing unwanted elements from your photographs, fixing color, adding other photographic elements to existing photos, adding creative gradients to your photos, using brushes to enhance photographs, and more!

Register online at: www.cmcommunityed.coursestorm.com

post_text: I'm sure everyone has heard the saying "As American as Apple Pie!" Well, students in Mr. Menth's Global Studies learned that apples didn't actually originate in North America! The first apple seeds came over in the Mayflower. As a class, they explored the impact apples have had on our nation, from the mythical Johnny Appleseed to WWII soldiers. Apples may not have started in our nation but we've made them our own, just like pasta, pizza, tacos and more! Best of all, each student got a little taste of apple pie, nothing but smiles in Global Studies!

The first apple seeds came over in the Mayflower. As a class, they explored the impact apples have had on our nation, from the mythical Johnny Appleseed to WWII soldiers. Apples may not have started in our nation but we've made them our own, just like pasta, pizza, tacos and more! Best of all, each student got a little taste of apple pie, nothing but smiles in Global Studies!

Today, Cedar Mountain FFA students attended GITS and CLC to learn about leadership, FFA, and skills to bring back to the chapter!

#NewStaffSpotlight

My name is Kelly Susa. I am the new ag teacher, FFA advisor, and JH volleyball coach at Cedar Mountain. I graduated last spring from the University of Wisconsin- River Falls with a degree in Agricultural Education and Sustainable Agriculture. In my free time, I enjoy camping, traveling, and making things (usually with my Cricut or sewing machine!)
